<TEXT>
miners among the most outspoken 
critics of the former communist rulers have become the shock 
troops of presidentelect ion iliescu during antigovernment 
protests 
neglected during more than four decades of communist rule the 
miners have enjoyed the biggest rewards of the december revolution 
that toppled dictator nicolae ceausescu higher salaries more food 
and less work 
though their presence in the pits is vital to the countrys 
growing energy needs iliescu and his ruling national salvation 
front have called miners to bucharest three times since the 
revolution to act against government opponents 
while iliescu has pledged to move romania toward a freemarket 
pluralistic society he has relied on the tactics of the former 
hardline communists rather than western standards of democratic 
dialogue to deal with protest 
traditionally when communist bosses thought their political 
fate was in danger they asked the workers to come and help them 
said stelian tanase editor of the anticommunist weekly 22 
now the neocommunists largely making up the front are 
appealing to the miners viewed as the workers advance guard who 
received everything they wanted from the government tanase said 
in a controlled communist society the shows of support posed 
little danger but relying on such tactics during a turbulent 
postrevolutionary period has proved bloody and destabilizing 
observers said 
iliescus game is a very dangerous one using the miners 
against other civilian groups such as students and intellectuals 
can lead to unforeseen consequencessaid emil hurezeanu a 
romanian exile and editor at munichbased radio free europe 
iliescu still thinks as a communist people like him who have 
been trained as communists since childhood cannot discard the mold 
too easily wrote vladimir tismaneanu a professor of romanian 
stock who lives in philadelphia in the independent newspaper 
romania libera 
until the december revolution that deposed and executed former 
communist dictator nicolae ceausescu romanias 70000 miners 
worked more and received less pay and food than their soviet bloc 
colleagues 
most work in mountainous western transylvania dominated the 
largest coal basin of the jiu valley where 30000 coal miners went 
on strike in 1977 demanding a fiveday week sixhour day free hot 
meal and retirement at 50 
ceausescu taken aback by the biggest work protest in communist 
romania initially gave in but later rescinded most concessions 
the now disbanded secret police arrested hundreds of miners and 
their leaders disappeared 
the front a loose organization of excommunists technocrats 
and industrial workers set to improving the living standard of 
workers especially the vocal miners shortly after taking power 
in the revoution 
in january iliescu 60 a former communist party secretary met 
miners leaders and agreed to their demands adding alpine chalets 
as a bonus 
according to some romanians iliescus aim was primarily to 
appease miners but they said that at the same time he may have 
realized he could manipulate them to the fronts advantage 
days later iliescu made a televised appeal for their support to 
counter a major antigovernment demonstration thousands of miners 
arrived in bucharest and attacked an opposition party headquarters 
corneliu coposu president of the national peasants party had to 
be rescued by an armored personnel carrier 
on feb 19 a day after opposition demonstrators stormed and 
ransacked government headquarters 5000 miners came to bucharest 
again to show support for the front they warned they would return 
in case of further trouble 
early thursday thousands of miners poured into bucharest at the 
governments request after antigovernment demonstrators stormed 
and set fire to police and interior ministry buildings 
the violence started early wednesday when clubwielding police 
routed anticommunist demonstrators who had blocked university 
square for 53 days 
operating as vigilantes or paramilitary groups the helmeted 
miners their faces smudged with coal dust stopped cars checked 
identities made home searches confiscated or destroyed property 
and clubbed anyone they wanted 
its clear that they had all the logistical support provided 
by the government a western analyst said on condition of 
anonymity 
they came on buses or trains from as far away as maramures 
300 miles northwest of bucharest and in the capital they were 
given food and milk from army trucks the whole thing was well 
organized the analyst said 
