nearly a million people have been asked 
to conserve water after farmers failed to block a hole in a canal 
that supplies bristol and surrounding communities 
a culvert collapsed thursday night beneath the gloucester and 
sharpness canal north of this city of about 375000 located about 
100 miles west of london 
farmers threw straw bales barrels and an old farm gate wrapped 
in plastic into the whirlpool created by water rushing through the 
hole but could not stem the leak 
the collapse of the culvert allowed more than a million gallons 
of water to escape 
it was like a bath without the plug in but on an enormous 
scale said jeremy williams spokesman for the bristol water 
company 
the 18mile canal carries more than 30 million gallons of water 
a day to serve an area around bristol of more than 1000 square 
miles the leak reduced the water supply by twothirds williams 
said 
we do not yet know what caused the collapse but the culvert 
is 170 years old and it might have just given up williams said 
adding that repairs were expected to take a week 
about a million customers were asked to conserve water while 
supplies from reservoirs in the mendip hills were pumped in 
