<TEXT>
americans are vacationing from the amazon to the 
himalayas fueling a phenomenon called adventure tourism that 
has unleashed protests over the footprints left behind 
adventure tourism accounts for 10 percent of the us travel 
industry or 13 billion a year and no one knows how big it will 
grow 
the debate is heating up over the impact of tourist intrusion on 
some of the most remote and ecologically fragile regions left in 
the world including antarctica and the galapagos islands 
the expeditions are growing in popularity particularly among 
older americans with money to burn and a burning desire to visit 
the last frontier lands seen only by a lucky few in their youth 
proponents say the trips promote ambassadors for the earth 
critics complain of litter contact with remote tribes and 
disruption of breeding among protected wildlife 
theres clearly a trend toward these type of expeditionary 
visits to remote places in the world said bruce manheim an 
environmentalist seeking tourist controls of one of the hottest 
travel destinations antarctica 
travel agents and tour operators are targeting affluent and 
welltraveled americans with an urgent message go now before 
environmental destruction of earths final frontiers is complete 
if you dont go now you are going to miss it said new york 
travel agent chip snyder who specializes in customized tours 
he urges tourists to visit such places as brazil papua new 
guinea and indonesia 
james barnes an environmentalist for friends of the earth a 
washingtonbased lobbying group said adventure tourism has 
positive and negative consequences 
on the one hand its always useful to have intelligent and 
outwardly looking people to look at places in need of protection 
and it helps to provide a constituency for protection he said 
but the scale of these activities is growing at such a pace 
that it does provide cause for concern to a lot of environmental 
groups 
he pointed to the galapagos an equatorial island chain in the 
pacific 620 miles off south america 
scientists warn of unchecked tourism endangering the ecosystem 
there the desolate archipelago is invaded each year by thousands 
of tourists and the scientists say some are disobeying rules 
littering and disrupting wildlife 
ecuador which annexed the islands in 1832 has considered 
stemming the influx by imposing stiff tariffs on foreign visitors 
about 800 tourists visited the frozen continent of antarctica in 
1988 and nearly 3000 in 1989 with more than 4000 tourists 
expected in the upcoming decembertofebruary season 
this may be just the tip of the iceberg said manheim who 
has called for strict regulation of tourist activities near 
wildlife breeding sites and coordination of cruise ship visits to 
protected areas 
travel to the himalayas also has risen 
sir edmund hillary the 70yearold new zealand adventurer who 
pioneered the route up mount everest in 1953 complained last march 
of tourist development destroying the pristine innocence of the 
majestic mountains 
the living standards are increasing but the beautiful tracks 
and valleys have been littered he said 
