<TEXT>
under an agreement between the two 
germanys east germany has agreed to return property confiscated by 
the former communist government or pay compensation to the original 
owners 
the property issue has been one of the most contentious as the 
two germanys move toward merging their economies 
former owners of property in the east who fled to the west 
immediately after the war or after communist east germany was 
founded in 1949 have been returning to stake claim on property 
they contend is still theirs 
also friday west germanys unification committee comprised of 
representatives of all parties in parliament agreed on a treaty 
that paves the way for economic unity july 2 
parliamentary ratification of the agreement was expected late 
next week 
the property agreement was the result of weeks of negotiations 
between the german governments it was outlined in a fourpage 
statement read at a news conference by rudolf seiters chief of 
staff for chancellor helmut kohl 
the agreement was part of overall accord on upcoming monetary 
and economic unification representatives from the west and east 
had been meeting to iron out that and other issues 
the statement said the rights of east german renters living in 
disputed apartments or on disputed property would be protected 
according to east german law 
for east germans who bought appropriated land or who own 
buildings which were erected on confiscated property a socially 
acceptable compensation was to be worked out either through 
exchange of property of similar value or other unspecified 
compensation it said 
the accord however does not apply to property confiscated 
during the 19451949 soviet postwar administration of the territory 
that later became east germany seiters said he said the soviets 
and east germans balked at that idea 
it was not immediately clear how much of the property in 
question was taken during the four years after the war and 
officials could not be reached for comment friday night 
seiters said it would be up to a future joint german parliament 
to make a final decision on any governmental compensation for 
property seized in the four years after the war 
the agreement for the return of private assets confiscated by 
the east german government applies to germans who fled east germany 
from 1949 on and will also extend to nationalized companies 
the statement said either the entire company would be returned 
to the original owner or some form of compensation would be made 
seiters said the east german government was working on a program 
to outline the time frame in which applications for return of 
property or compensation could be submitted and that experts from 
both countries would continue working out the details of the 
compensation program 
