the government has decided to inject 85 million 
into britains foundering film industry in an effort to turn around 
seven years of hard times 
prime minister margaret thatcher told a meeting of film industry 
representatives friday that the money will be used over the next 
three years to help british filmmakers seeking coproductions 
elsewhere in europe 
theater attendance soared last year in britain but british film 
production reached its lowest level since 1981 britain made only 
25 films last year mrs thatcher said 
some production companies have gone bust the best known is 
goldcrest films which helped bring chariots of fire 
gandhi and the killing fields to the screen the 
independent companys work between 1977 and 1986 received dozens of 
awards including 19 oscars but it collapsed after a series of 
flops 
the lag followed a boom in the early 1980s when the industry 
seemed reborn when chariots scriptwriter colin welland 
accepted the 1982 academy award for best film he declared 
triumphantly the british are coming 
british films have not benefited from the government support 
given the industry in countries like australia and france 
the british film industry has a proud record of excellence 
but film production in this country has been on the decline mrs 
thatcher said this is an industry in which britain cannot just 
compete we can excel 
the meeting was attended by sir richard attenborough the 
director of gandhi and david puttnam who produced chariots 
of fire 
i am hugely encouraged puttnam said all we have asked 
for over a long period of time is a hearing and that is what we 
have had 
he called the 85 million a goodwill gesture 
what is more important over the long term is the formation of 
the working parties he said the committees are to look into 
setting up government incentives to attract private money 
mrs thatcher also said the industry will study taxes on film 
production and report back to the government 
in addition the government will provide an additional 263500 
to support the 1990 european film awards in glasgow scotland 
the film industry representatives said their main concern was 
the lack of british investment in its own film industry they said 
money was available from the united states but any profits go 
right back across the atlantic 
