<TEXT>
secretary of state james a baker iii met 
with his japanese counterpart and said afterward it will take a 
strong effort from both countries to reach a final trade 
agreement by the end of the month 
the united states and japan are rushing to draw up a final 
agreement aimed at correcting a trade imbalance between the 
countries in time for next months sevennation economic summit in 
houston 
our two nations the two largest economies in the world have 
an obligation to offer constructive international leadership 
baker said in a statement after the 3hour meeting at the fairmont 
hotel we believe we can do so as global partners 
foreign minister tara nakayama told baker that japan was 
making efforts to correct the trade imbalance between the 
nations a japanese government spokesman told reporters 
less than two weeks remain before japan and the united states 
are scheduled to wrap up trade talks and draw up a formal list of 
economic reforms fridays discussion reportedly was called so the 
officials could attempt to revive the talks which have become 
stalled in recent months 
nakayama made it clear that the japanese government is making 
efforts to reduce its current trade surplus makoto yamanaka a 
spokesman for the japanese foreign minister told reporters 
yamanaka stopped short of saying that fridays discussion had 
revived the stalled talks known as the structural impediment 
initiative saying only that progress was important to both 
governments 
the spokesman declined to discuss the specifics of the meeting 
of baker and nakayama but he said the two talked about eastern 
europe china and mongolia as well as the trade imbalance 
baker said it would take a good strong effort on both sides 
to come up with a final agreement 
one point of contention is that the bush administration has 
called for japan to spend at least 9 percent of its gross national 
product on government construction projects yamanaka said the 
foreign minister still had some resistance to a specific spending 
requirement 
the united states trade deficit with japan is 49 billion a 
year 
in april the two countries tentatively outlined a series of 
economic reforms japan agreed to open its retailing system 
increase spending on public works projects strengthen antitrust 
legislation and loosen restrictions on foreign investment 
the united states pledged to cut its federal budget deficit and 
take measures to increase savings and investment 
the sii talks begun last year have been bogged down lately 
with japan indicating its made all the concessions it can 
meanwhile the united states is characterizing the april accord as 
a way station with more concrete language needed to carry out 
