the opening day of the sixday meeting featured a rallystyle 
joint gathering of conference task forces on drugs and 
homelessness several mayors warned that festering racial and 
ethnic tensions in major cities could explode unless city and 
federal governments work together to address housing needs and 
poverty which the mayors blamed for exacerbating drug use and 
violence 
if we wait until there is a crisis it will be too late said 
philadelphia mayor w wilson goode we have the opportunity to 
deal with it before it gets out of hand 
fridays opening session was full of antiwashington rhetoric 
but short on specific solutions the chairman of the session 
boston mayor raymond flynn said he wanted an open discussion of 
urban problems from which the mayors could draft proposed policy 
statements for the conference to consider next week 
flynn opened the session with a scathing attack on federal 
spending priorities 
federal policy towards our cities and towards economic 
opportunity today is as bankrupt as the corrupt savings and loans 
which are robbing our young peoples future he said 
while we waited at washingtons back door for a few crumbs for 
urban america these bandits heisted over 300 billion from our 
nations treasury flynn said 
these are funds that could have been used for job training 
for college scholarships for helping young families buy their 
first home as well as building a national economy set to compete 
with europe and japan 
flynn chairman of the task force on homelessness was among 
mayors blaming federal aid cutbacks they said have left cities too 
poor to provide job training to keep youths off streets and away 
from crime the mayors hope to lobby collectively for money they 
believe can be saved from a reduced need for military spending 
the mayors are expected to request that more antidrug money go 
directly to cities instead of states but the national governors 
association said in a letter to the mayors made public friday that 
it favored the current system under which states can award grants 
to cities but have latitude in spending the federal money 
