<TEXT>
few men could have felt as utterly alone as 
charles de gaulle on the evening of june 18 1940 
as the tall uniformed french general strode into the london 
studios of the bbc to make his first broadcast to france his 
country was collapsing under the german blitzkrieg its government 
was suing for peace a shellshocked populace was resigned to defeat 
de gaulles gamble seemed a pathetic exercise in selfdelusion 
at 49 virtually unknown outside military circles he lacked 
troops guns money and friends the collaborationist french 
government would shortly sentence him to death 
de gaulle wrote later that he felt like the survivor of a 
shipwreck a man on the shore of an ocean proposing to swim 
across 
fifty years later de gaulles broadcast is a hallowed memory 
for france a symbol of defiance against all odds but in 1940 
there was no rush to his banner 
de gaulle had led his tanks gallantly against the german 
onslaught and remained in france until june 17 leaving for england 
only when defeat became inevitable 
the british had hoped leading politicians would come to carry on 
the fight and winston churchill was disappointed that no one more 
senior than de gaulle showed up 
but the british prime minister immediately recognized the 
general as a comrade de gaulle correctly predicted the americans 
and soviets would join the war and that hitler would go down in 
five years 
that kind of fighting talk appealed to churchill you are 
alone well i shall recognize you alone he told de gaulle on 
june 27 
the relationship between the two titans soon faltered de 
gaulle an instinctive anglophobe showed his hosts little 
gratitude 
he could be breathtakingly arrogant petty setbacks sent him 
into rages leonard miall a bbc editor remembers de gaulles fury 
because his june 18 broadcast was not recorded for posterity 
the bbcs equipment was needed that day to record churchills 
this was their finest hour speech but de gaulle wasnt 
interested in excuses 
he tore strips off the bbc in general and me in particular for 
failing to appreciate the historical importance of the occasion 
miall said in an interview i had never encountered such an angry 
man 
churchill complained of de gaulles insufferable rudeness 
the americans felt the same franklin d roosevelt mocked the 
generals pretensions dwight d eisenhower couldnt stand him 
mary borden an english novelist who knew de gaulle wrote 
understandingly to come to the british as a suppliant with the 
disgrace of his nation burned on his forehead and in his heart was 
intolerable but he could look to no one else his own people 
failed him the french officials reviled or snubbed him the troops 
turned their back on him the response to his appeal was pitiable 
the weaker his position the more arrogant he became 
driven by a mystical faith in frances greatness de gaulle was 
loftily unrepentant 
i shall yield nothing of the elements which make up that 
greatness he told a visitor in london the weaker i am the 
more intransigent i shall be in defending our rights 
as the allies gained the upper hand de gaulles free french 
army swelled and when france was chosen for the allied invasion of 
europe the general and his army assumed greater importance 
de gaulles war was an epic human drama its repercussions 
reflected in his bouts of hostility toward britain and the united 
states lasted through his decade as president of france until his 
death in 1970 
militarily his role in world war ii was not crucial but his 
primary goal in london was to pick up the broken sword and 
transform france from humiliated collaborator to victorious ally 
in that the lonely cantankerous courageous visionary 
triumphed utterly 
</TEXT>
