<TEXT>
betty ellis a 64yearold minneapolis 
housewife says intellectual curiosity drew her to join nine 
others sunday on a 10day journey billed as appalachia third 
world in the united states 
global exchange a nonprofit research education and action 
center in san francisco that arranged the reality tour hopes 
it will lead mrs ellis and her fellow travelers on a path to 
political activism 
political awareness tours cater to a different breed from the 
adventure or educational trips promoted by many travel agencies 
and might be considered the opposite of club meds antidote to 
civilization 
tour members give up luxury hotels museums monuments and 
romantic dinners to take the opportunity to reshape their views of 
the world 
the 500 per person appalachian tour for example will go to 
tennessee kentucky and virginia to visit a child care center 
agricultural food and housing projects the mountain womens 
exchange and the highlander center in new market tenn which has 
fought poverty racism sexism and environmental destruction since 
the 1930s 
there wont be any whiskeysipping with toothless old men in 
overalls whittling cedar sticks at a country store as a 
tennessee columnist wrote in conjuring up stereotypes the tourists 
might be looking for 
global exchanges tours in fact are supposed to break down 
stereotypes inspire people to get involved in community 
organizations and build ties between people in developed and 
developing areas the socalled first and third worlds 
poverty can be found in every state global exchange is 
planning other us trips that may include the san francisco bay 
area but the group chose appalachia because of its inspiring 
example and rich history of organizing 
we felt it was very important to highlight community 
organizing in the united states as well as the third world said 
laurie adams tour coordinator for global exchange we dont feel 
you have to go all the way to the third world to see some of the 
problems that are facing communities there 
grassroots organizing is a key aspect of the new activism of the 
1990s an outgrowth of the citizen diplomacy efforts of the past 
decade and a step beyond the protest movements of the 60s and 
70s participants span a wide range of ages and professions 
we encourage people on the tours to get involved afterward 
but in whatever ways that are comfortable for them said adams 
24 weve had grandmothers come and get articles published in 
local papers its encouraging to see that it takes some courage 
and wanting to have a challenge to go on these trips but you can 
have a lot of fun too 
global exchange claims 5000 members nationwide but has a staff 
of only five working in a modest office in an ethnically diverse 
part of san francisco two other staff members run a store in the 
city that sells arts and crafts from the third world and two 
staffers work in haiti and honduras 
the group founded 1 years ago has published books and 
promoted speakers on us policy third world issues and grassroots 
organizing in the past year it also has run trips to haiti india 
honduras el salvador nicaragua brazil mozambique and zimbabwe 
among the people who have gone on the trips are community 
workers and those seeking alternatives to typical vacations 
ranging in age from 18 to 75 and including doctors nurses city 
officials nuns business people lawyers and housewives 
rachel chapman a health worker in los angeles went to 
mozambique and zimbabwe and said she met people in high levels in 
the government and families in the countryside 
the personal interaction stimulates and helps each of us 
become more capable as leaders she said 
the trip to appalachia initially set off a storm of adverse 
publicity and in may west virgina was dropped from the tour 
of course not all of appalachia resembles the third world 
adams said just as in brazil there are wealthy parts and poor 
parts but some of the characteristics are the same 
the resources such as coal are extracted for the benefit of 
rich outsiders while local workers live in poverty and face 
dangerous working conditions a lot of the control is in the hands 
of distant politicians and corporate boards not in the hands of 
local people environmental destruction is wrought by things such 
as the coal mining industry and health care education and 
transportation systems arent fairly distributed 
