<DOCNO> AP900616-0100 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
fear of the aids virus is so prevalent in the 
united states that onethird of the people who reported 
aidsrelated discrimination do not even have the disease an 
american civil liberties union report said saturday 
this study shows how extraordinarily persistent discrimination 
remains in this country even after science has proven there is no 
risk of casual transmission said nan d hunter principal author 
of the study 
the aclu study epidemic of fear will be presented at the 
sixth annual conference on aids in san francisco this week the 
study was compiled from information provided to the aclu by 260 
legal and advocacy groups across the country 
discrimination hurts the fight to control aids because many who 
have the disease refuse to be tested out of fear they will become 
victims of intolerance experts say 
about 13000 complaints of aids or hivrelated discrimination 
came into the 260 agencies between 1983 and 1988 hiv is the virus 
that causes aids 
discrimination reports increased by 50 percent during 1988 
following an 88 percent increase in 1987 the report said 
the study found that aidsrelated discrimination occurs 
nationwide cutting across lines of race gender ethnicity and 
sexual orientation even people who do not have the disease but 
associate with people who do are frequent targets of 
discrimination the report said 
most discrimination cases were based on fears of catching the 
disease racial prejudice or antihomosexual prejudice according 
to the study 
thirty percent of the people who reported discrimination were 
not hiv positive the study said twentyone percent of the 
discrimination complaints were from victims who thought they were 
targeted due to their risk of becoming hiv positive through a job 
lifestyle or other factors 
nine percent felt they were the victims of discrimination merely 
because of their proximity to someone who was hiv positive that 
closeness might be through a family relationship or by providing 
care or some type of services to an infected person the report 
said 
hiv discrimination is the no 1 obstacle to controlling the 
epidemic in this country because people are afraid to come forward 
and be tested said carisa cunningham a spokeswoman for the gay 
mens health crisis in new york we are not able to reach 
people because discrimination makes them afraid to come forward 
recommendations for fighting hivrelated discrimination include 
upgrading enforcement of antidiscrimination laws training lawyers 
in hivrelated issues and tightening the regulation of insurance 
practices 
consistent antidiscrimination laws are needed around the 
country because some states have strict laws while others have no 
laws the study said enforcement of the americans with 
disabilities act which takes effect in 1992 must become a top 
priority in the next decade ms hunter said 
the act bans discrimination against people with disabilities 
including people who are hiv positive and will make it possible to 
file discrimination charges in federal court 
the report was hailed by dr mervyn silverman american 
foundation for aids research president who said it points out how 
much still needs to be done in the area of aids education 
polls show that a significant percentage of americans know 
aids is spread through sex and drugs silverman said but at 
least 25 percent still believe it could be spread casually and when 
asked they said the best way to avoid getting the disease is to 
not be associated with anyone who has the disease 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

