emissions of carbon dioxide 25 percent within 15 years to combat 
global warming known as the greenhouse effect a government 
official said friday 
scientists say the odorless colorless gas could cause higher 
temperatures by collecting on the outer edges of the earths 
atmosphere and trapping heat within that process could produce 
changes in the worlds climate 
frankfurter allgemeine newspaper said that highly industrialized 
west germany with about 61 million people inhabiting an area 
roughly the size of oregon now releases 716 million tons of 
carbon dioxide a year into the atmosphere 
reducing the emissions by 25 percent by the year 2005 would mean 
a cut of nearly 180 million tons annually it said 
a cabinet committee group was set up wednesday to work out 
details for the project said uwe fritche he is a member of the 
enquete commission a federal panel of experts that evaluates 
policy options on climate change 
fritche said officials are also studying ways of drastically 
cutting carbon dioxide emissions in east germany as quickly as 
possible after the two countries are united 
east germany which heavily depends on brown coal as an energy 
source has the highest per capita emission rate in the world with 
224 tons per year per person the newspaper report said west 
germanys is about half that level 
carbon dioxide is released during the burning of fossil fuels 
its already clear that energy efficiency will be the main 
means to achieve the goal of cutting emissions 25 percent 
fritche told the associated press in a telephone interview 
he said the government is considering taxing emissions to 
encourage cutbacks in the industrial and private use of 
carbondioxide producing fuels including heating oil 
in britain prime minister margaret thatcher has committed her 
country to a 30 percent reduction in its carbon dioxide emissions 
by the year 2005 
