droughtplagued southern californias major 
water wholesaler will use satellite photographs to detect 
overwatering of large tracts of land officials said friday 
the project which begins july 3 will not mean daytoday 
monitoring of overwatering said tim skrove a spokesman for the 
metropolitan water district of southern california which serves 15 
million people in six counties 
authorities will use the photographs to assess irrigation levels 
over an extended period of time skrove said 
this isnt an instance where were going to be spying on 
people skrove said were going to be spying on water use 
primarily in broad categories such as parks golf courses 
cemeteries or even residential neighborhoods but certainly not 
individual homes 
where overwatering is detected water district officials expect 
to contact local water districts subdivision developers or 
operators of parks golf courses or cemeteries to encourage 
conservation measures such as landscaping that requires less water 
skrove said 
there wont be any new photographs only pictures taken since 
october 1988 by landsat satellites which orbit 450 miles above 
earths surface said tracy walklet vice president of terramar 
resource information services inc 
the mountain view calif computer software and systems company 
will buy enhance and analyze the photos under an 80000 contract 
approved tuesday by the water districts board of directors 
to the best of our knowledge this is the first time this 
technology is going to be applied to urban area for gauging water 
conservation potential skrove said 
terramar will use the photos to determine the amount of 
irrigated land and the intensity of watering in the districts 
