<TEXT>
a prominent aids activist is calling for riots 
at this weeks sixth international aids conference and while most 
demonstrators wont go that far many have promised to disrupt the 
meeting with protests inside and outside the convention hall 
the call for riots came from larry kramer one of the founders 
of the aids coalition to unleash power or act up 
it is the most militant aids organization and kramer may be its 
most militant member 
in articles published in gay newspapers around the country 
kramer wrote every human being who wants to end the aids 
epidemic must be in san francisco screaming yelling furiously 
angry protesting at this stupid conference we must riot 
act up is a grassroots group without leaders or a hierarchy it 
was founded in new york in 1987 and now has perhaps 2000 members 
there twentyfive chapters have sprung up across the country some 
with several hundred members 
of the conference organizers kramer said my feeling is these 
are the same idiots putting on this conference who have bumbled the 
epidemic for 10 years and made mistake after mistake 
if you really want my gut feeling he said in an interview 
last week i think the war against aids has been lost 
san francisco police say they expect demonstrations at the 
convention but no violence 
outside of mr kramer we dont know of anybody talking riot 
or violence said sgt jerome senkir were hoping for a 
peaceful conference i think at this point thats going to happen 
as kramer pointed out in his articles the aids meeting which 
begins wednesday in san francisco provides an unparalleled 
opportunity for activists to deliver their message 
some 12000 scientists and 1800 members of the news media are 
registered to attend the conference was established as an annual 
forum for presentation of the latest scientific reports on aids 
but increasingly is becoming the target of protests 
last year in montreal the opening of the conference was delayed 
for an hour when 200 activists seized he podium to demand better 
access to aids drugs and an end to discrimination peaceful 
demonstrations continued later outside the convention center 
larger and more disruptive demonstrations are expected this year 
some protesters will remain outside the meeting boycotting the 
conference to protest a policy that allows the us immigration and 
naturalization service to bar foreigners infected with the aids 
virus 
the new york chapter of act up will not boycott the meeting at 
least 50 of its members have registered and they promise to carry 
their protests inside 
protests are liable to occur at the most visible events or at 
anything where a bush administration official or a member of the 
executive committee is at the podium said peter staley of act up 
new york 
the executive committee is a group of scientists that sets 
policy for the aids clinical trials group the governments program 
for testing new aids drugs it is run by the national institutes of 
health 
there will be two major messages well be trying to deliver 
there said staley first off is the rage our community is 
feeling now with the ins secondly he said we want to deliver 
the message to the scientific community that they have failed thus 
far in reducing aids to a chronic manageable disease from the 
death sentence that it is now 
act up has become adept at organizing angry demonstrations its 
most recent protest occurred at the national institutes of health 
a thousand activists gathered there in may to demand increases in 
federal aids research eightytwo were arrested 
even before the demonstration the national institutes of health 
was so upset by act ups criticisms that it took the unusual step 
of sending science reporters a detailed 30page response 
like it or not weve got a debate going about the 
governments aids research effort said staley during the may 
demonstration there was debate in the corridors of the nih he 
said arguments broke out as to whether we were right or wrong 
at the same time act up has worked quietly behind the scenes to 
help change government policy its members now are consulted by the 
nih and the food and drug administration 
we seem to have access to anyone we want said charles 
franchino a member of the act ups treatment and data committee 
when we meet with government people theres the specter of 3000 
people standing behind us and thats whats gotten us in the 
door 
kramers call for riots has divided activists it was criticized 
by gay and lesbian groups in san francisco 
san francisco is not an angry town like new york is kramer 
said 
one group there he noted plans a quiet candlelight protest 
but militants elsewhere have put the city on notice 
i do know that the city is terrified that there really are 
going to be riots and i suspect it will be very much a police 
state for those days he said 
after montreal there was a lot of hope this year there is a 
lot of despair because that hope has simply not appeared 
drugs continued to be tested slowly in a rigid system kramer 
said and for many people with aids it already is too late 
were talking about another savings and loan scandal he 
said were all going to wake up and its going to cost 500 
billion 
new york state has just reported that its annual expenses for 
aids care topped 1 billion for the first time last year in 10 
years researchers have projected that one in 24 people in new york 
city will have aids a new aids infection occurs in the united 
states every minute 
the figures are grotesque and no ones paying attention to 
them kramer said 
in a letter to activists who opposed his call to riot kramer 
wrote you are free not to riot and you are free to criticize my 
call to riot 
and we are all free to die 
