<TEXT>
trading in belgiums bourse never has 
been highprofile but a dispute over control of marketmoving 
information here has grabbed attention of brokers and regulators 
far beyond the borders 
the stock exchange is battling a group of belgian and 
international news outlets over who has the right to release news 
first 
the news group has accused the exchange of seeking to monopolize 
the news violating the european communitys fair competition rules 
and press freedom the group includes reuters ltd the largest 
financial information reporting service 
the exchange has said it wants to level the playing field for 
market participants by becoming a clearinghouse for 
marketsensitive corporate news under a stock market reform bill 
now under government review 
presently companies release news to the exchange and the press 
at the same time under the reform only the exchange would get the 
news then release it to investors and traders through a datbase to 
which the media could subscribe 
although some say this is strictly a domestic fight others fear 
it could have more profound implications for trading elsewhere 
especially in view of other events that suggest the world is moving 
to 24hour global trading 
the 12nation european community is scrutinizing the belgian 
dispute with special concern because it plans a communitywide 
trading system after 1992 the system presumably would have uniform 
rules for disclosure of information that could affect stock prices 
the debate over the issue already has led the belgian government 
to review the stock market reform plan 
we are taking this very seriously said bernard snoy an 
aide to finance minister philippe maystadt 
reuters and several belgian media groups have complained to the 
government the stock market is misinterpreting the bill they argue 
that if the bourse gets to handle corporate news before the media 
this will violate ec laws on clarity in corporate matters and fair 
competition 
they say the stock market cannot get company news to the public 
quickly they also say it cant be done without risking insider 
trading abuses in which stock market insiders can act on corporate 
news before others can 
this could institutionalize insider trading said herman 
smedts manager of electronic information at the financieel 
ekonomische tijd a financial daily 
but bourse officials say their method avoids insider trading by 
giving the bourse a chance to suspend dealings in a company stock 
before the information is released 
also they say by releasing news after trading has closed they 
can assure all investors will see reports in the media the next day 
and can act on it simultaneously when trading reopens 
we are mainly concerned that information gets to all people at 
the same time said jean peterbroeck head of the brussels stock 
market commission a panel intended to make sure the exchange 
functions in an orderly manner 
there is also money at stake 
the bourse a nonprofit outfit has created bdb its own 
database service the media groups say that by channeling 
information to bdb the exchange gets a monopoly on news and gets 
to finance the computer trading system the brussels bourse bought 
in 1988 
its partially true we are out to make money said bdb 
general manager jeanpierre monmart 
but we never had the idea of monopolizing market news 
organizing yes monopolizing no 
the media groups fearful of losing customers point to the new 
york stock exchange as an example of how the stock market could set 
its news policy 
the nyse requires companies to release their news to the 
exchange and to reuters and the dow jones co the worlds two key 
financial news groups simultaneously the paris and frankfurt 
exchanges have similar rules 
for their part the brussels bourse points to the london 
international stock exchange which gets a first crack at corporate 
news 
brussels also says the media have ulterior motives 
reuters which already receives instant data on stock prices 
volumes and some price bids wants access to even more exchange 
information 
they could only want that to mount their own trading system 
to supplant conventional exchanges said one bourse official who 
asked not to be named 
reuters says it only wants the same type of information other 
markets provide it and the other media groups proposed creating a 
cooperative owned by information vendors to replace bdb 
the two alternatives one requiring simultaneous disclosure 
the other giving a stock exchange precedence are likely to be 
debated as exchanges across the ec work to establish a 
communitywide stock trading system 
sources said the ec federation of stock exchanges has agreed in 
principle that their price information program for europe pipe 
would resemble the london stock exchange media groups have said 
they will challenge that 
