manhattans south street seaport was a frenetic 
commercial center in the 19th century but fell victim to 
technological leaps in moving goods that made its wharves and 
merchants obsolete 
the message has not been lost on another business landmark 
nearby the cavernous new york stock exchange 
this past week the big board took steps ultimately designed to 
avoid the same fate as the seaport now a trendy singles spot of 
bars and restaurants where oceangoing clippers are just quaint 
relics from the precivil war days 
nyse chairman john phelan confirmed plans to ease into 
computerized afterhours trading which could lead to full 24hour 
trading by the year 2000 the nyse also released a study of stock 
volatility aimed at showing that the nations biggest securities 
market is sensitive to the anxieties of all investors 
although details of the afterhours trading plan must still be 
worked out the aim is to recover business lost to competing 
exchanges and companies that are trading nyse stocks on their own 
when the nyse is closed 
there is some volume going overseas and wed like to capture 
some of that volume back phelan said 
the big board remains by far the preeminent us place to buy 
and sell stocks but in recent years a growing number of investors 
who want to do business in the offhours are going to london or 
tokyo a reflection of what appears to be an inexorable march 
toward a nonstop global marketplace 
other investors have found it more efficient to execute trades 
via technologically advanced nyse rivals in the united states the 
overthecounter nasdaq system for example uses computers to 
match buyers and sellers and is expanding into offhours trading 
this september when it will open at 330 am eastern time 
by contrast the nyse has clung to an oldfashioned group of 
marketmaking specialists although they use computers to make 
the flow of trading more efficient the specialist system still 
hinges on humantohuman contact on the big board floor which 
opens weekdays at 930 am and closes at 4 pm 
the nyses traditional reluctance to expand hours has played a 
partial role in its eroding share of business it handled only 692 
percent of all trades in listed stocks last year a record low 
exchange earnings fell to 629 million last year a 40 percent 
drop from the 1045 million earned a year earlier 
the nyse is taking a look at afterhours trading basically 
because of competitive pressures said joseph hardiman chairman 
of the national association of securities dealers which runs the 
nasdaq system theyre trying to be responsive by telling issuers 
they will be able to provide something 
the nyses other signal of responsiveness to customers came 
earlier in the week when its market volatility and investor 
confidence panel disclosed findings of a study into causes of 
stockprice volatility 
the most important recommendation was the use of trading halts 
during times of market stress but many securities professionals 
remain opposed to such an idea arguing it could worsen panicky 
selling by investors trying to get out of a market before it closed 
some suggested trading halts also could have the ironic side 
effect of driving business to less restrictive markets abroad 
in other business and economic news this past week 
more signals emerged suggesting a slowing economy retail and 
wholesale prices rose modestly in may easing pressure on 
inflation the government reported it also said the trade deficit 
shrank dramatically in april reflecting lower demand for imported 
oil and autos 
a takeover specialist ensnared in the ivan boesky insider 
trading scandal received a 2month prison term one of the mildest 
punishments meted out in a fouryearold crackdown on securities 
fraud martin a siegel who allegedly took suitcases of cash from 
boesky in return for insider tips could have received 10 years in 
prison but he cooperated with prosecutors to implicate others 
standard amp poors corp a leading debtrating agency lowered 
its opinion of creditworthiness of ford motor co and chrysler 
corp reflecting growing weakness in the automotive industry the 
rating downgrade means ford and chrysler will find it more costly 
to borrow money 
