<TEXT>
financially strapped philadelphia received 
another blow friday when standard amp poors corp lowered its 
ratings on 13 billion in city bonds citing chronic deficit 
operations 
city financial director betsy reveal who called the news 
disappointing but not unexpected said the decision could cost 
the city 30 million in future years in extra interest 
the citys general obligation bonds were downgraded two rating 
notches from bbbplus to bbb the company also said 236 million in 
bonds issued by the philadelphia redevelopment authority and 
philadelphia parking authority were downgraded to bbb 
the rating is one level above what standard amp poors considers 
the minimum investment grade that offers a high level of 
security the last time the citys bond rating dipped below 
investment grade was in 1976 
it clearly will increase our costs for future borrowing 
reveal said 
standard amp poors pointed to this fiscal years city deficit 
estimated to be 60 million when the year ends june 30 as a sign 
of chronic fiscal imbalance 
the creditrating company added that the citys 21 billion 
budget scheduled to go into affect july 1 does not bode well for 
restoration of fiscal stability 
